<div id="review_40664253" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/40664253" />
    <a title="Jasmine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/948622-jasmine"><img alt="Jasmine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1552595409p2/948622.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/40664253?book_show_action=true">Dec 22, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jasmine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jasmine" href="/user/show/948622-jasmine">Jasmine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/948622-jasmine?shelf=well-that-sucked">well-that-sucked</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer40664253" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3703772679675106901"><br/>This won’t be going in the favorite pile. It seemed to lead nowhere. The ending was unsatisfying and I was left feeling as if the narrator just stopped narrating. I don’t regret reading it, I just feel like I missed something. <br/><br/>Did I miss something? Was this book really about…nothing? <br/><br/>I was able to take something away from it though. <br/><br/>I learned that I am not the only one that thinks something but can&apos;t articulate it. <br/><br/>James, the protagonist in this book very often answers every question with &quot;I don</span>
  <span id="freeText3703772679675106901" style="display:none"><br />This won’t be going in the favorite pile. It seemed to lead nowhere. The ending was unsatisfying and I was left feeling as if the narrator just stopped narrating. I don’t regret reading it, I just feel like I missed something. <br /><br />Did I miss something? Was this book really about…nothing? <br /><br />I was able to take something away from it though. <br /><br />I learned that I am not the only one that thinks something but can't articulate it. <br /><br />James, the protagonist in this book very often answers every question with "I don't know" despite having dwelled said question from every angle possible. He has the right reply... but only ever in thought. <br /><br />He has trouble communicating his thoughts accurately. It’s not for a lack of vocabulary, for he is highly educated. It’s not for a lack of feeling; he feels exactly what he’s supposed to. <br /><br />I find that words flow so effortlessly in my mind and weave such perfect, intelligent and reasonable thoughts. It is only when I attempt to articulate these thoughts that I witness the death of them. The words die before they even leave my mouth. I watch as a person’s brow furrows and they tilt their head ever so slightly to the side, confused. Once it’s left the womb of my mind, the thought becomes tainted, muddled and broken. It’s no longer the pure “thought of” reflection that dwelled in my head. By the time I’ve finished speaking it’s morphed into something all together different. <br /><br />This is why James always says “I don’t know”<br />He does know. He just doesn’t want to watch his thoughts die. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3703772679675106901" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


