    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1027253126" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1027253126" />
    <a title="Maria" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1929752-maria"><img alt="Maria" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1027253126?book_show_action=true">Aug 15, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maria" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maria" href="/user/show/1929752-maria">Maria</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780312428167" href="/book/show/6277983-someday-this-pain-will-be-useful-to-you">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1929752-maria?shelf=coming-of-age">coming-of-age</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1929752-maria?shelf=ya">ya</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1027253126" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13469382523845961888">I rather enjoyed this book. This is supposedly YA, but I like some YA books, and even if I&apos;m already a grown up, I suppose I could still relate to some of James&apos;s observations. (See the quotes section for his smart, wry observations). It&apos;s structured like a diary, with dates at the beginning of chapters. Another reason why I loved this book is because it is also very funny. I found myself smiling, and sometimes even laughing out loud. For example, when Gillian explains that she wants to be calle</span>
  <span id="freeText13469382523845961888" style="display:none">I rather enjoyed this book. This is supposedly YA, but I like some YA books, and even if I'm already a grown up, I suppose I could still relate to some of James's observations. (See the quotes section for his smart, wry observations). It's structured like a diary, with dates at the beginning of chapters. Another reason why I loved this book is because it is also very funny. I found myself smiling, and sometimes even laughing out loud. For example, when Gillian explains that she wants to be called Gillian with a hard 'G' and she tells her mother that pronouncing a child's name incorrectly is a subtle form of abuse, her mother replies, "If I were going to abuse you, there would be nothing subtle about it." Totally made me smile. :) I just love stuff like that. <br /><br />I read this in 3 days (which is quite something because I hardly have time to read books anymore... always feeling pressured that soon I have to go to work or something) but this was very easy to read, plus, I kind of like James because he's so sensitive and fragile, but I do agree with some of the reviewers about how sometimes you just want to shake him and tell him to snap out of it, as his anxiety about college is completely unfounded. Anyway... they did worse things to him in the movie version (SPOILER ALERT: one of the kids punched him). I must admit I can't pretend to know what's going on in the mind of a depressed teen. But to me, the incident in DC was kind of a letdown. I thought for sure something very horrible had happened. So, anyone looking for a plot-driven kind of novel won't really find it here. It's more of a character driven story (which I also like). <br /><br />Something that was omitted from the film is the part about 9/11. James apparently went to Stuyvesant and saw everything. That would be traumatic and I would have liked to see that in the film version. I liked how Cameron handled it in the book and how James relates it to his sadness. That part about when he remarks that disappearing and no one noticing that you have disappeared is a beautiful thing. I don't necessarily agree, but I can see why James would think so. <br /><br />The ending felt a little too abrupt... I was enjoying this book quite a bit, obviously, and wanted to read more, but I was noticing there were only a few pages left... :( Well, James goes on to college, which is very realistic. So while some readers might have complaints about how predictable that is-- that's how real life works out sometimes, and I liked that about this book. <br /><br />Also, the title seems a little melodramatic, but James also thinks so (I think). It's a quote from Ovid and was apparently the motto of a sailing camp James attended on the summer his parents divorced. Yet another reason why I liked this book: James remarks that such a sailing camp will never be fun. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13469382523845961888" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


